data.title: You read it in his voice. Admit it.
Three of the nastiest conventional weapons in use today.

images.description:
Cluster Munitions/Bombs

Colloquially known as firecracker rounds, these weapons are a large shell that is initiated by artillery or more often an aircraft. Within the shell there are a number of explosive sub-munitions. Depending on its size and type, a firecracker can hold from two very expensive smart rounds to over two thousand coke can like dumb submunitions. Once the shell is over the target, it cracks open and distributes its payload over a large area.

Firecrackers have a high failure rate within their bomblets. Testing on US cluster munition war stock had submunition dud rates from 2% up to 23% depending on the age of the shell. When used, the blast from other bomblets exploding affects those still dropping, resulting in further failures. The result is that cluster bombs tend to blanket an area in unexploded ordinance that will be dangerous to civilians for years post conflict.

Incendiary Weapons

Incendiary agents are any type of weapon designed to burn supplies, equipment, structures and personnel. The culprits are munition types laden with white phosphorus, thermite or magnesium. These compounds are persistent, almost impossible to put out and burn at extremely high temperatures. They will usually be mixed with high explosive shells to crack the externals of flammable infrastructure and launch the ignition sources further.

When immediate family members ask you for your IT help

images.description: Any IT person knows the struggle of family members calling for computer help here and there. It wasn't a huge pain, but after marrying and building the family out some more, I decided to simply treat the family as a small corporate network.

The plan was to gut out pretty much anything they had that couldn't be remotely administered. My brother, in-laws, parents, etc all wanted cameras which I hooked up years ago. The goal was to get all of this stuff centralized.  So this is what I came up with.

I bought a crap ton of Ubiquiti stuff as the backbone--mostly because the UNMS/Unifi management is simple enough. Plus, can you really beat a $35-40 gigabit router that features some pretty advanced things to it? These are residential homes so it's not like I need to push anything serious though them. Simple SNMP, OVPN, QOS, etc should suffice.

data.description:
I've been seeing complaints on Imgur: Too many ads! Too intrusive! Too much malware!

Yes, that's shitty of Imgur.

Here's what else I've been seeing: Off of Imgur, people complaining that direct links to images don't work unless they have Imgur open in another tab. Off of Imgur, people complaining that it doesn't work with their favorite "hover over a link and see it" browser extension. Off of Imgur, people saying that they don't bother opening Imgur links.

People saying they don't open Imgur image links. In favor of Tumblr image links. Because something with a direct Tumblr image link was more likely to reliably open an image.

Tumblr, guys. 

Tumblr is outdoing us on reliable image hosting.

Especially if you want to use a gif. Go ahead, try that on Imgur. It doesn't work. Upload a gif, you get an mp4. If you don't care about file formats, skip this paragraph. If you want to choose between gif and mp4, you can do that on Tumblr. Not here anymore.

Here's me being alarmist.

Here's me being paranoid.

Here's me warning you.

Back in my day, if you wanted to have a short URL that worked for embedding and linking, you uploaded your image to Photobucket. And then Photobucket got a little more finicky about the process, then more, and more, and now none of those images or links work anymore.

Now, Imgur is getting a little more finicky.

If you're here for the community, don't worry. Comment, message, make connections.

If you're here for the image hosting?

Rehost.

images.description: I’m going on my third year here, and I used to love it. Now, your app is a hot mess, and it seems like you guys have refused to listen to your community. We’ve begged and pleaded for you guys to do something about how buggy it’s become, yet nothing is done. AT LEAST offer some kind of paid non-ad version of the app. PLEASE. images.description: 1. The Yucatan Penninsula was so named because a Spanish explorer asked an indigenous Mayan what the area was called and the Mayan said something that sounded to the Spaniard like "yucatan". It actually meant "I don't understand you."

The two of them seem to have first met when Sulla was a young man and their relationship continued for at least 30 years. When Sulla retired (from his life-long appointment, but that's another story) Metrobius seems to have stayed with him until his death.

R.I.P Saudi college students sacrificed their lives attempting to save US kid’s lives and they did save them ! Imgur, let's never forget them.

images.description:
Selfless Saudi college students Theeb Alyami and his cousin Jaser Alrakah give their lives saving children from drowning in MA’s Chicopee. They sacrificed their lives attempting to save US kid’s lives and they did save them ! 

The students, Theeb Alyami, 27, and Jaser Alrakah, 25, were cousins studying at a local college in Massachusetts and were getting ready to graduate next month. The bodies of the Saudi students were recovered after extensive search.

The children were playing in the water and were caught in the current, according to reports. Several adults tried to help the children, but failed, the report said.

“On Friday my brother and his cousin were on a picnic next to the river when they saw a mother in distress trying to save her children, who now because of my brother and cousin are alive and have already been discharged from the hospital,” the brother of one of the Saudi victims told the Saudi newspaper Sabaq.  “The American media are referring to them as heroes.”

A State Police dive team and air wing helped in the search of the Saudi students. One of the victims was recovered on Friday. The search for the second victim stopped at sunset Friday, and resumed Saturday to no avail. On Monday morning, authorities found the body of the second victim.

Alrakah was an engineering student at Western New England University. Alyami was enrolled at the University of Hartford in a civil engineering program. The two universities issued statements in which they expressed their condolences to the Yami and Al Rakah families. The two universities affirmed that they appreciated the heroic stand of the two students who died while helping others and expressed their full solidarity with the families of the deceased.

University of Hartford President Greg Woodward issued a statement to the campus mourning his loss. "We will mourn this terrible loss together. In the days ahead, we will work with Theeb's family to determine the most appropriate way to honor his memory," the statement read.

data.title: Would you travel through space with this Robot?

images.description: Hey! We are the indie game studio Alt Shift and we are creating a story-driven rogue-lite game inspired by FTL  (Faster Than Light) and the Sci-Fi masterpiece: Foundation, by Isaac Asimov!

Space exploration in a procedurally-generated universe : Navigate through an infinity of detailed and violent planetary systems. Choose your path to the boss wisely to manage your limited resources and to avoid bloodthirsty enemy ships hunting you in the dark of outer space.

One of our goals in making Crying Suns was to make the player feel like the admiral of a battleship. Let's be honest, there's a lot more to being an admiral than deciding which type of missile to launch at an enemy. 
Our events are the vehicle that allows us to really sink our teeth into this idea. We've crafted over 300 entertaining and challenging events, with various outcomes for each, for you to experience on your journey through the galaxy.

Monty Python member Terry Gilliam has come out as a transgender lesbian
data.description:
Terry Gilliam has responded to the BBC diversity debate which referenced Monty Python by saying: “I tell the world now I’m a black lesbian.”

Gilliam was commenting on the row over diversity triggered by the BBC’s unveiling of its new comedy programming, announced in June, at which the BBC’s controller of comedy commissioning Shane Allen emphasised the corporation’s commitment to “the stories that haven’t been told and the voices we haven’t yet heard”. In response to a question about Monty Python’s Flying Circus, Allen said: “If you’re going to assemble a team now, it’s not going to be six Oxbridge white blokes. It’s going to be a diverse range of people who reflect the modern world.”

Speaking at a press conference at the Karlovy Vary film festival, where he was presenting his new film The Man Who Killed Don Quixote, Gilliam said: “It made me cry: the idea that ... no longer six white Oxbridge men can make a comedy show. Now we need one of this, one of that, everybody represented... this is bullshit. I no longer want to be a white male, I don’t want to be blamed for everything wrong in the world: I tell the world now I’m a black lesbian... My name is Loretta and I’m a BLT, a black lesbian in transition.”

He added: “[Allen’s] statement made me so angry, all of us so angry. Comedy is not assembled, it’s not like putting together a boy band where you put together one of this, one of that everyone is represented.”

Gilliam follows fellow Python member John Cleese’s angry response to Allen’s comment, who tweeted: “Unfair! We were remarkably diverse FOR OUR TIME ... We had three grammar-school boys, one a poof, and Gilliam, though not actually black, was a Yank. And NO slave-owners.”

Gilliam has previously attracted controversy for his comments on the MeToo campaign, likening it to “mob rule” and saying: “ It’s crazy how simplified things are becoming.”

https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/04/terry-gilliam-on-diversity-bbc-monty-python-black-lesbian

It's nice to see that they've still got it.

This is "shaft bottom", 1900' below the surface of a small town in Nevada.  This is a relatively shallow mine compared to most.  The mine I just transferred from in AZ was -7100', and the one before that in ID was -9300'.  Every mine is different.  Most are very wet, some are dry, most are hot as fuck, and some are freezing.  The danger involved in mining is unparalleled.  Once a week we have a "fataligram" safety meeting about some poor gentleman who left his family too soon.  I myself have had many brushes with death underground, some instances so bad that they keep me up at night.  It's wild and fast lifestyle, and the money and insurance is out of sight!  Just thought I'd share some of this craziness with my Imgurian family.

Edit: Wow! Thanks everyone!  And thanks for all of the interest shown.  A lot of people are asking about close calls, so I'll speed-type some shit out before work.

The company I work for specializes in sinking shaft.  We are the ones responsible for creating the giant hole in the ground.  I'm a mine/shaft electrician, and we deal with very high voltages (4160-13,800)all day long.  Essentially, I'm faced with a triple threat everyday.  

While running shaft cables one time, our work platform slowly ran into a 13,800V feeder cable, because the guy driving (running the bells) the work deck had become complacent and was not paying attention. The platform first punctured the neoprene coating, then tore into a strong steel armor the protects the cable.  Next would've been the conductors, wich would've resulted in an arc blast.  Arc blasts are supposed to be 4 times hotter than the surface of the sun and basically disintegrates you immediately.  All 3 of us should've been smoked.  

To be continued... Time for work.

Send boobs and 'gines to help me through the day, please!

images.description:
It happened at the shelter four years ago when I wanted to adopt a cat. I'm making an edit here because I wanted to flesh out a bit more the reason I went to a shelter. 

Two days before my visit I had to put down my beloved cat, Pepe. she was close to 11 years of age, and had unfortunately developed a malignant tumor in her belly, and it grew rapidly. My veterinarian offered me two choices; an operation, or euthanasia. she also told me that an operation wasn't a guarantee that the cat would make a healthy recovery, and that the cancer might come back soon, and more agressive. Pepe was in pain. It showed. She wasn't eating anymore, and was constantly hiding. I took the very hard decision to give her peace. It was a very hard moment, and anyone who's ever had to have a pet put down will understand. I stood in front of her, holding her head in my hands so she could at least see a familiar face before going. I painfully saw the life fading away in her eyes as the vet did her job. I gave her one last kiss, paid, and exited the office wetting the pavement. 

Grief isn't a pleasant feeling. from my experience there was but one way to reverse the polarity of that emotion, and that of having lost a familiar presence in my life: adopt another cat. Don't get me wrong, it wasn't to replace Pepe, as you can't replace a beloved pet. It was to switch the grief, to hope, from pain, to happiness. 

Back to the shelter, to days later. 

Saw a couple of cats. some old ones, an agressive one, and a kitten too young to be adopted yet. I was almost ready to leave when I saw this small one, hiding in her litter box. I almost missed her because of that. The person responsible for adoptions told me that the cat, a female, was scheduled to be put down because she was terrified of everyone, and everything. Her file didn't tell a pretty story. She was beaten on a regular basis by her owners, and then one day she was "rescued" by neighbors who had enough of it. But then she escaped, and wasn't found until a few days later in a local park. Since these neighbors could not keep her, they brought her to the shelter, hoping she would get a better chance in life. 

The veterinarian could hardly give her a check up because she panicked, and tried to hide. And seemingly, "panicked" is a light word to describe how she reacted according to the staff. She was never agressive though, but always fled, and tried to hide as if the whole place was on fire. Even with all the care at the shelter she never improved, and was given very poor chances at being adopted. And she didn't. No need to tell you that animals don't stay indefinitely in shelters. And since she was deemed "non-adoptable" because of her constant fear, and because no one wanted her, she was set to be put down. 

As I arrived in the shelter to adopt she had but one day left to live. I told the employee I wanted to see her. She agreed, but warned me beforehand. It took several tries to pull her out of her litter box, where she constantly hid. She was then put in a towel, then brought into a small room where people can have a contact with the animal they're interested in. She panicked, of course. She immediately fled behind behind a chair and made herself as small as possible, tail tucked in, and ears flat. Typical reaction of a cat who knows nothing but physical abuse. But I managed to take her. Then I held her. I squinted at her, meaning that I posed no threat. I looked in her eyes, and I saw that despite everything, she truly wanted to be loved, and cared for. Despite the multiple warnings by the staff that it would not be an easy road, even expecting me to return with the cat, I signed the papers and adopted her. 

It wasn't easy. It took a *tons* of patience, and love, but it was all rewarded.

Today, Zoey is loving cat. She's calm, climbs on me for scritches, sleeps with me, and often climbs on me while I watch movies to purr of contentment, and eventually fall asleep. I'm very happy to have her, and to have been able to give her the happy life she deserves. And yes, she loves watching movies with me. Her favorite is The Aristocats.

TLDR: Cat at shelter was set to be put down because of constant fear. Deemed non-adoptable. I adopted her, and now she's a happy, happy cat.

Edit: Wow, Front page! Is that what it looks like? Never been here. Well, in any case I'm happy that Zoey's story has touched you, in one way or another. Encouraged by the success of this post, I decided to write another one about another cat I saved three months later from a certain death.

You can read about it here: https://imgur.com/gallery/h4zWkGE

Many thanks again for all those who commented, and the upvotes and send pussy pics! Or nudes.  :)

data.title: This man is Nathan Larson. He's running for Virginia State Congress.

images.description:
Larson is a self-admitted pedophile, rapist, and white supremacist. He's admitted to raping his wife, who after a divorce won custody of their 3 year-old daughter and filed a restraining order against him. Sadly, she later committed suicide. I thought I'd share a bit about him before linking to a Huffpost article on the guy, which has yet more information outlining what a terrible, terrible person Nathan is.

According to Larson’s campaign manifesto, his platform as a “quasi-neoreactionary libertarian” candidate includes protecting gun ownership rights, establishing free trade and protecting “benevolent white supremacy,” as well as legalizing incestuous marriage and child pornography.

In the manifesto, Larson called Nazi leader Adolf Hitler a “white supremacist hero.” He urged Congress to repeal the Violence Against Women Act, adding, “We need to switch to a system that classifies women as property, initially of their fathers and later of their husbands.” He also showed sympathy for men who identify as involuntary celibates, or incels, suggesting it is unfair that they “are forced to pay taxes for schools, welfare, and other support for other men’s children.

“Why doesn’t every pedo just focus on making money so they can get a pedo-wife and then either impregnate her with some fucktoys or adopt some fucktoys?” he wrote on the platform in October. “That would accommodate both those who are and aren’t into incest. And of course, the adoption process lets you pick a boy or a girl," wrote Larson on a pedophile community site.

Larson said that the word “pedophile” is “vague” and “just a label,” adding that it’s “normal” for men to be attracted to underage women. He said he did not commit any crimes. He's identified himself as a "hebephilic rapist", noting that he's not your typical incel as he'd had sex by raping his ex-wife.

But wait, there's more.

In a 3,300-word essay on incelocalypse.today, titled “Here’s How to Psyche Yourself Up to Feel Entitled to Rape,” Larson tells other members: “Don’t forget: feminism is the problem, and rape is the solution.”

He's also a convicted felon after having sent a death threat to the President in 2008, though somehow not for all this crazy shit.
